06536nam a22007335i 9780889206076DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20062000xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808892060767 a10.51644/97808892060762doi  a(DE-B1597)667495  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPR9080b.P575 2000 7aLIT0070002bisacsh04a820.9/917124122100aPostcolonizing the Commonwealth :bStudies in Literature and Culture /ced. by Rowland Smith. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2006] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (222 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tContributors -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPostcolonial/Commonwealth Studies in the Caribbean: Points of Difference -- tProximities: From Asymptote to Zeugma -- tLooking in from ‘‘Beyond’’: Commonwealth Studies in French Universities -- tClimbing Mount Everest: Postcolonialism in the Culture of Ascent -- tAfrikaners, Africans and Afriquas: Métissage in Breyten Breyten-bach’s Return to Paradise -- tInheritance in Question: The Magical Realist Mode in Afrikaans Fiction -- tNatal Women’s Letters in the 1850s: Ellen McLeod, Eliza Feilden, Gender and ‘‘Second-World’’ Ambi/valence -- tRural Women and African Resistance: Lauretta Ngcobo’s And They Didn’t Die -- tFive Minutes of Silence: Voices of Iranian Feminists in the Postrevolutionary Age -- tFAS and Cultural Discourse: Who Speaks for Native Women? -- tCan Rohinton Mistry’s Realism Rescue the Novel? -- tDislocations of Culture: Unhousing and the Unhomely in Salman Rushdie’s Shame -- tA Vision of Unity: Brathwaite, Ngugi, Rushdie and the Quest for Authenticity -- tCowboy Songs, Indian Speeches and the Language of Poetry -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWomen and resistance in Iran; cowboy songs; fetal alcohol syndrome; the conquest of Everest; women settlers in Natal. What do these topics have in common? The study of what used to be called Commonwealth literature, or the new literatures, has by now come to be known as postcolonial study. This collection of essays investigates the status of postcolonial studies today. The contributors come from three generations: the pioneers who introduced study of the “new” literatures into university English departments, the next generation who refined and developed many of the theoretical positions embodied in postcolonial study, and the next, much younger, generation, who use the established practices of the discipline to investigate the application of this theory in a wide range of cultural contexts. Although the authors write from such different starting points, a surprisingly similar set of images, phrases and topics of concern emerge in their essays. They return constantly to issues of difference and similarity, the re-examination of categories that often appear to be too rigidly defined in current postcolonial practices, and to concepts of sharing: experience, ideas of home, and even the use of land. Postcolonizing the Commonwealth: Studies in Literature and Culture offers an intriguing analysis of the state of postcolonial criticism today and of the application of postcolonial methods to a variety of texts and historical events. It is an invaluable contribution to the current debate in both literary and cultural studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCommonwealth literature (English)xHistory and criticism. 0aCommonwealth literature (English)xStudy and teaching (Higher). 0aPostcolonialismxStudy and teaching (Higher). 0aPostcolonialism. 4aLiterary Criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Books & Reading.2bisacsh1 aBardolph, Jacqueline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 